On Android I have a big issue with RenderTarget2D, when Graphic context is lost and recreated they cannot be used anymore as GraphicDevice.SetRenderTarget(rt) crashes with a framebuffer incomplete message. 

To replicate simply add the following lines to Cartblanche's RenderTarget2D sample:

protected override void OnActivated (object sender, EventArgs args)
{
    base.OnActivated (sender, args);
    if (renderTarget != null) {
        renderTarget.Dispose ();
        renderTarget = new RenderTarget2D (GraphicsDevice, GraphicsDevice.PresentationParameters.BackBufferWidth,
                       GraphicsDevice.PresentationParameters.BackBufferHeight, false, SurfaceFormat.Color, DepthFormat.None);}
    oneTimeOnly = true;
}

I managed to track a possible problem in the constructor stack of Rendertarget2D, at line 1060 of Texture2D:

GL.GenTextures(1, ref this.glTexture);

results in this.glTexture = -1, wich i think brings an error due to incomplete frambuffer...
(this happens only after context is lost and recreated)

Currently the property Handle in the class OpenTKGameWindow looks like below. 

```
public override IntPtr Handle { get { return IntPtr.Zero; } }
```

However if you add the below to Initialize() you can actually set the pointer and return it. Very very useful to people like me making 3rd party libraries to compliment MonoGame. 

```
var ii = window.WindowInfo;
object inf = window.WindowInfo;
var pi = (inf.GetType()).GetProperty("WindowHandle");
_windowHandle = ((IntPtr)pi.GetValue(ii, null));
```

And now the handle property can be useful.

```
public override IntPtr Handle { get { return _windowHandle; } }
```

I hope this is helpful and can be added in. Access to the underlying window when working with Linux would be very nice.
